<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="7" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,649,1900]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,649,675]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dana" authorityYear="1853" box="[281,407,649,675]" class="Malacostraca" family="Synopiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Synopiidae</taxonomicName>
with accessory eyes*. Gnathopods 1 and 2 simple with slender, long carpus and propodus. Pereopods 3–7 short, dactylus/unguis short, stubby (
<figureCitation box="[744,824,685,711]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1831,1855]" captionTargetBox="[160,1423,179,1796]" captionTargetId="figure-15@9.[151,1436,179,1806]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 1. Representative habitus illustrations of tironin genera. Tiron spiniferus (from Sars, 1895 pl. 140, ♀ 8 mm); Pseudotiron miratus sp. nov. (this paper, ♀, 4.5 mm); Tironella pervicax comb. nov. (from J.L. Barnard, 1967 fig. 84, ♂ 4.7 mm); Glandulotiron pilocaputis sp. nov. (this paper, ♀, 6.3 mm); Metatiron tropakis (from J.L. Barnard, 1967 fig. 45, ♀, 4.9 mm); Minitiron bellairsi comb. nov. (from Just, 1981 fig. 1, ♀ 2.4 mm). a and b, dactylus and unguis of pereopods 3–7: a, stubby; b, pre-stubby." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6572025" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6572025/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Fig. 1a</figureCitation>
), or pre-stubby (
<figureCitation box="[1016,1097,685,712]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1831,1855]" captionTargetBox="[160,1423,179,1796]" captionTargetId="figure-15@9.[151,1436,179,1806]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 1. Representative habitus illustrations of tironin genera. Tiron spiniferus (from Sars, 1895 pl. 140, ♀ 8 mm); Pseudotiron miratus sp. nov. (this paper, ♀, 4.5 mm); Tironella pervicax comb. nov. (from J.L. Barnard, 1967 fig. 84, ♂ 4.7 mm); Glandulotiron pilocaputis sp. nov. (this paper, ♀, 6.3 mm); Metatiron tropakis (from J.L. Barnard, 1967 fig. 45, ♀, 4.9 mm); Minitiron bellairsi comb. nov. (from Just, 1981 fig. 1, ♀ 2.4 mm). a and b, dactylus and unguis of pereopods 3–7: a, stubby; b, pre-stubby." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6572025" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6572025/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Fig. 1b</figureCitation>
) with short, hooked claw and curved counter-seta on dactylus. Uropod 3 longer than uropods 1 and 2, at least as long as elongate, fully split telson.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,649,1900]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
* 
<taxonomicName authority="Dana, 1852" authorityName="Dana" authorityYear="1852" box="[219,444,793,820]" class="Malacostraca" family="Synopiidae" genus="Synopia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[219,309,794,820]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Synopia</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Dana, J. D." box="[316,444,793,820]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" pagination="297 - 316" refId="ref48851" refString="Dana, J. D. (1852) On the classification of the Crustacea Choristopoda or Tetradecapoda. American Journal of Sciences and Arts, Series 2, 14 (appendix), 297 - 316." type="journal article" year="1852">Dana, 1852</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Karaman, 1986" authorityName="G. Karaman" authorityYear="1986" box="[497,820,793,820]" class="Malacostraca" family="Synopiidae" genus="Telsosynopia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[497,642,793,819]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Telsosynopia</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Karaman, G. S." box="[648,820,793,820]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" pagination="117 - 166" refId="ref49642" refString="Karaman, G. S. (1986) Several poorly known or new species of families Synopiidae and Phoxocephalidae from the Mediterranean Sea (Contribution to the knowledge of the Amphipoda 158). The Montenegrian Academy of Science and Arts Glasnik of the Section of Natural Sciences, 5 (114), 117 - 166." type="journal article" year="1986">Karaman, 1986</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
also have accessory eyes, but otherwise differ in all the diagnostic characters of the 
<taxonomicName authority="Just, 2022" authorityName="Just" authorityYear="2022" box="[465,577,829,855]" class="Malacostraca" family="Synopiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" status="new subfamily" subFamily="Tironinae">Tironinae</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
